<p>
The <code>handleActivationRequest</code> function is a wrapper for the <a href="/docs/(PHP) handleAPIRequest">handleAPIRequest</a> function that only accepts requests from MinoCloud to activate the <a href="/docs/Apps">app</a>. It should be used on an address (PHP page) that you designate as the <code>Activation URL</code>.
</p>

<div class="heading">handleActivationRequest(<code>callback</code>)</div>
<p>
<code>callback</code><br />
<code>Type: String</code><br />
The name of the function that will be called with the username of the new user as <code>appUser</code>. If there is anything wrong with the structure of the request then the callback will not be called and <code>handleAPIRequest</code> will end the request and write an error to the response.
<br />
<br />
If the <code>callback</code> function returns <code>true</code> then the <a href="/docs/Apps">app</a> will be activated. Any other value will be shown as an error in the activation process.
</p>

<div class="heading">Example Usage</div>
<p>
Because the <code>minocloud</code> object is unique for each request, it contains the username of the authenticated user in the <code>appUser</code> key if they were successfully authenticated.
</p>
<p>
If the <code>request</code> includes a URL parameter named <code>minocloud_session_cookie</code> then this value will be set as the cookie and a "Location" header will be sent. This will end the request and the <code>callback</code> will not be called.
</p>
<pre>
$minocloud = new MinoCloud("ExampleApp","3XaMpL3ApPaP1K3Y");

$minocloud->handleActivationRequest('myActivationFunction');

function myActivationFunction($appUser){
	/* Save any folders that the app is going to use
     * for this user's data then respond with true. */
	return true;
};
</pre>